div.p:
A. Though Man be not Saved by the Tenor of the Covenant of Works, the condition whereof is perfect Obedience;
Gal. 2. 16. Rom. 10. 5. but by the Covenant of Grace, the condition whereof is true Faith:
Rom. 10. 9. yet is sincere Obedience in doing good Works, necessarily required of all Believers for divers Reasons, besides that before-mentioned.

A. Christ (in the Greek Tongue)
 and Messiah (in the Hebrew) signify Anointed;
Act. 10. 38. so that this Name imports his being invested with three great offices, by God, which he undertook for the effecting Mans Salvation: All which Offices were conferred by the Ceremony of Anointing in Ancient Times.

                 A. We beg, that God's Sovereign Authority may be acknowledged in all the World, and his Laws obeyed; Psal. 67, 2. 3, 4. 2 Thes. 3. 1 that his Kingdom of Grace may be propagated, by the Conversion of Jews, Turks, and other Infidels;
                 Rom. 10. 1. Psal. 2. 8. and in the Church, promoted and preserved; 2 Thes. 1. 11. 12. Psal. 28. 9. that we, in particular, may be, and continue to be, his true Subjects; Ps. 119. 36, 80. that his Kingdom of Glory may be

hastned; Rev. 22. 20. and lastly, that the Power of Sin, Satan, and whatsoever is contrary to his Kingdom in any sort, may be abolished. Rom. 16. 20. 1 Joh. 3. 8.
